@LeakerApple Humane and Rabbit shipped. 

Vapourware is for things that don’t ship at all.

Anyway the point is that success is probably not in the cards for this.

@aidanshandle VR hasn't completely flopped; there is still a good audience of a few million people who like it. What flopped was being forced to put a scuba mask on your face. 

I still love my Apple Vision Pro, but after an hour, it hurts my face. When glasses come, then we're going to reintroduce all the magic to everybody again and see where the industry lies after that. 

The next 18 months are going to be highly entertaining.

@LukeElin You asked the key question: Can openness beat walled gardens? 

Mark Zuckerberg's glasses only support the Meta ecosystem (Instagram, WhatsApp, Facebook, etc.). If that remains true for the Apple and Google versions, I think it leaves a space for a truly open pair of glasses. 

I don't know who is going to be the one to provide that open alternative—there are others out there like Mentis Glass—but there are just too many unanswered questions yet to know whether an open pair of glasses could actually reach a mainstream audience, rather than just 100,000 to a million early adopters.

@NinosMaron @pickle Everything this company is doing is striking the right notes, but they are up against some big monsters coming soon. Anyway, I bought a pair. We'll see:

1. If they actually show up
2. If they are as cool as the demo

@DlwildWild That was me that misunderstood; my mind was somewhere else. 

If we're just talking about an acquisition, I still see a good reason to keep it independent. Putting it inside Tesla makes it serve Tesla's needs too much, and Neuralink will be out on the cold steps. I'd rather keep it independent if I was Elon and share the resource amongst all the companies equally, almost as an internal customer. 

Sorry for going off there—I was thinking you were talking about Grok inside the car.
